04945nam a22006735i 9780748629732DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222009stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486297327 a10.1515/97807486297322doi  a(DE-B1597)614832  a(OCoLC)1306540504  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aHIS0380002bisacsh04a978.00721 aJones, Karen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe American West :bCompeting Visions /cKaren Jones, John Wills. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b15 B/W illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tIntroduction -- tPart One: Old West -- t1. Lewis and Clark: Mapping the West -- t2. Frontier Germ Theory -- t3. ‘The Gun that Won the West’ -- t4. Cowboy Presidents and the Political Branding of the American West -- tPart Two: New West -- t5. Women in the West: The Trailblazer and the Homesteader -- t6. Women in the West: The ‘Indian Princess’ and the ‘Lady Wildcat’ -- t7. The Wild West Defiled: The American Indian, Genocide and the Sand Creek Massacre -- t8. The Thirsty West: Grand Canyon, Hoover Dam and Las Vegas -- tPart Three: Recreating the West -- t9. The Western Renaissance: Brokeback Mountain and the Return of Jesse James -- t10. The Arcade Western -- t11. Turn here for ‘The Sunny Side of the Atom’: Tourism, the Bomb and Popular Culture in the Nuclear West -- t12. Re-creation and the Theme Park West -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe American West used to be a story of gunfights, glory, wagon trails, and linear progress. Historians such as Frederick Jackson Turner and Hollywood movies such as Stagecoach (1939) and Shane (1953) cast the trans-Mississippi region as a frontier of epic proportions where 'savagery' met 'civilization' and boys became men.During the late 1980s, this old way of seeing the West came under heavy fire. Scholars such as Patricia Nelson Limerick and Richard White forged a fresh story of the region, a new vision of the West, based around the conquest of peoples and landscapes.The American West: Competing Visions explores the bipolar world of Turner's Old West and Limerick's New West and reveals the values and ambiguities associated with both historical traditions. Sections on Lewis and Clark, the frontier and the cowboy sit alongside work on Indian genocide and women's trail diaries. Images of the region as seen through the arcade Western, Hollywood film and Disney theme parks confirm the West as a symbolic and contested landscape.Tapping into popular fascination with the Cowboy, Hollywood movies, the Indian Wars, and Custer's Last Stand, the authors show the reader how to deconstruct the imagery and reality surrounding Western history.Key FeaturesA general, lively and provocative introduction to the history of the American WestAn intellectual challenge to existing approaches and ideas about the WestA summary of the latest key arguments about the meaning of the WestIncludes 15 b+w illustrations and numerous maps  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezWest (U.S.). 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / Americas (North, Central, South, West Indies).2bisacsh1 aWills, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074862251140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074862973240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748629732423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748629732/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh Universi